For each drug, the number of successes over 10 trials follows a binomial distribution, Binomial(10, 0.7). The probability that the maximum number of successes for any drug exceeds eight is equivalent to the probability that at least one drug has more than eight successes (i.e., 9 or 10 successes).

The probability for a single drug having more than eight successes is:
- P(S > 8) = P(S = 9) + P(S = 10)
- P(S = 10) = (0.7)^10 ≈ 0.0282475249
- P(S = 9) = C(10,9) * (0.7)^9 * (0.3) = 10 * (0.7)^9 * 0.3 ≈ 10 * 0.040353607 * 0.3 = 0.121060821
- P(S > 8) ≈ 0.0282475249 + 0.121060821 = 0.1493083459

The probability that all three drugs have at most eight successes is:
- P(all ≤ 8) = [P(S ≤ 8)]^3
- P(S ≤ 8) = 1 - P(S > 8) ≈ 1 - 0.1493083459 = 0.8506916541
- P(all ≤ 8) ≈ (0.8506916541)^3 ≈ 0.615625436

The probability that the maximum exceeds eight is:
- P(max > 8) = 1 - P(all ≤ 8) ≈ 1 - 0.615625436 = 0.384374564

Rounded to three decimal places for reasonable significant figures, the probability is 0.384.

