To calculate the energy of one mole of UV photons with a wavelength of 300 nm, the formula for the energy of a photon is used: \(E = \frac{hc}{\lambda}\), where \(h\) is Planck's constant (\(6.626 \times 10^{-34} \, \text{J·s}\)), \(c\) is the speed of light (\(3.00 \times 10^8 \, \text{m/s}\)), and \(\lambda\) is the wavelength. For one mole of photons, this energy is multiplied by Avogadro's number (\(N_A = 6.022 \times 10^{23} \, \text{mol}^{-1}\)).

