 The unit of the answer should be  .
Solution: The expected value \(E(Z)\) is computed as follows. The random variables \(X_1\) and \(X_2\) are independent and identically distributed exponential random variables with mean \(\theta = 2\), so the rate parameter is \(\lambda = 1/\theta = 1/2\).

Define \(Y_1 = \min(X_1, X_2)\) and \(Y_2 = \max(X_1, X_2)\). The minimum of two independent exponential random variables with rate \(\lambda\) is exponential with rate \(2\lambda\). Here, \(2\lambda = 2 \times (1/2) = 1\), so \(Y_1 \sim \text{Exponential}(1)\), and \(E[Y_1] = 1\).

The maximum can be expressed as \(Y_2 = X_1 + X_2 - Y_1\). Thus, \(E[Y_2] = E[X_1] + E[X_2] - E[Y_1] = 2 + 2 - 1 = 3\).

The cost is \(Z = 2Y_1 + Y_2\), so \(E[Z] = 2E[Y_1] + E[Y_2] = 2 \times 1 + 3 = 5\).

Alternatively, \(Z = 2Y_1 + Y_2 = 2 \min(X_1, X_2) + \max(X_1, X_2)\). Since \(\max(X_1, X_2) = X_1 + X_2 - \min(X_1, X_2)\), it follows that \(Z = 2 \min(X_1, X_2) + (X_1 + X_2 - \min(X_1, X_2)) = X_1 + X_2 + \min(X_1, X_2)\). Therefore, \(E[Z] = E[X_1] + E[X_2] + E[\min(X_1, X_2)] = 2 + 2 + 1 = 5\).

The result is exact and does not require rounding.

