Problem:  Of a group of patients having injuries, $28 \%$ visit both a physical therapist and a chiropractor and $8 \%$ visit neither. Say that the probability of visiting a physical therapist exceeds the probability of visiting a chiropractor by $16 \%$. What is the probability of a randomly selected person from this group visiting a physical therapist?
 The unit of the answer should be  .
Solution: The probability of visiting at least one provider is 1 minus the probability of visiting neither, which is 1 - 0.08 = 0.92.  
Using the inclusion-exclusion principle, the probability of visiting at least one is also equal to P(physical therapist) + P(chiropractor) - P(both).  
Given P(both) = 0.28, this equation is: P(physical therapist) + P(chiropractor) - 0.28 = 0.92, so P(physical therapist) + P(chiropractor) = 1.20.  
Additionally, P(physical therapist) = P(chiropractor) + 0.16.  
Substituting, let P(chiropractor) = c, then P(physical therapist) = c + 0.16.  
The sum becomes (c + 0.16) + c = 1.20, so 2c + 0.16 = 1.20.  
Solving, 2c = 1.04, c = 0.52.  
Thus, P(physical therapist) = 0.52 + 0.16 = 0.68.  
Verification: P(physical therapist) + P(chiropractor) = 0.68 + 0.52 = 1.20, and P(at least one) = 1.20 - 0.28 = 0.92, which matches 1 - 0.08. The difference is 0.68 - 0.52 = 0.16, as given.

