Simplifying the left side:  
\[
\frac{1}{15} \left( \frac{8R}{R + 9} + \frac{63}{R + 9} \right) = \frac{1}{15} \cdot \frac{8R + 63}{R + 9} = \frac{8R + 63}{15(R + 9)}
\]

So the equation is:  
\[
\frac{8R + 63}{15(R + 9)} = \frac{151}{300}
\]

Cross-multiplying:  
\[
300(8R + 63) = 151 \cdot 15 \cdot (R + 9)
\]

Calculating each side:  
Left side: \(300 \times 8R = 2400R\), \(300 \times 63 = 18900\), so \(2400R + 18900\).  
Right side: \(151 \times 15 = 2265\), so \(2265(R + 9) = 2265R + 2265 \times 9 = 2265R + 20385\).

The equation is:  
\[
2400R + 18900 = 2265R + 20385
\]

Rearranging terms:  
\[
2400R - 2265R = 20385 - 18900
\]  
\[
135R = 1485
\]  
\[
R = \frac{1485}{135} = 11
\]

Verification:  
If \(R = 11\), total balls in second urn is \(11 + 9 = 20\).  
P(both red) = \(\frac{8}{15} \times \frac{11}{20} = \frac{88}{300}\).  
P(both blue) = \(\frac{7}{15} \times \frac{9}{20} = \frac{63}{300}\).  
P(same color) = \(\frac{88}{300} + \frac{63}{300} = \frac{151}{300}\), which matches the given probability.

The final answer is 11.

